version: 1
display_name: VCFJ-9X-000101 - The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations HCX Apache HTTP service must implement HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) to protect the integrity of remote sessions.
global_description: |-
  HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) instructs web browsers to only use secure connections for all future requests when communicating with a web site. Doing so helps prevent SSL protocol attacks, SSL stripping, cookie hijacking, and other attempts to circumvent SSL protection.
osfinger:
  - VMware Photon OS-5
refs:
  disa_stig:
    - VCFJ-9X-000101
  srg:
    - SRG-APP-000516-WSR-000174
  cci:
    - CCI-000366
  nist:
    - CM-6 b
benchmark_id:
  vcf9_operations_hcx_httpd:
    type: custom
    desc: The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations HCX Apache HTTP service must implement HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) to protect the integrity of remote sessions.
    control_id: VCFJ-9X-000101
    scored: true
    profile:
      - default
    information: |-
      Verify a header is present to configure HSTS.

      At the command prompt, run the following:

      # cat /opt/vmware/config/apache-httpd/hcx-virtual-hosts.conf | sed -n "/^<VirtualHost\s\*:443>/,/<\/VirtualHost>/p" | grep -i "Header"

      Example output:

      Header set Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000 ; includeSubDomains"

      If a header directive is not present to configure "Strict-Transport-Security", this is a finding.
    rationale: |-
      HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) instructs web browsers to only use secure connections for all future requests when communicating with a web site. Doing so helps prevent SSL protocol attacks, SSL stripping, cookie hijacking, and other attempts to circumvent SSL protection.
    remediation: |-
      Navigate to and open:

      /opt/vmware/config/apache-httpd/hcx-virtual-hosts.conf

      Find the "VirtualHost" section listening on port 443 and add or update the following line:

      Header set Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000 ; includeSubDomains"

      Reload the configuration by running the following command:

      # systemctl reload httpd
